text: Okay, I admit I was geeking out beyond belief seeing the bagulins, the marcyan, the collector(?), what looks like but probably isn't Point Central and above all the ASTROSHIP. (Sorry if none of that makes sense, going by the danish edition). The plot doesn't look like it will have anything to do with the story it's named for (sensible, since Star Wars stole half of that story decades ago), but at least the movie is adapting some great moments from all over the series instead. However, I'm pretty disappointed in the overall production design - how does the actual Valerian movie end up looking less like Valerian than the Fifth Element did? With the same director?  My biggest worry is Laureline's actress, though - she seems to be playing a COMPLETELY different character, which is a crying shame. (Also way too young for the role, imo.) The classic dynamic of warm, open-minded and clever Laureline lovingly mopping the floor with uptight dork Valerian would have been AMAZING and fresh in a movie - instead it looks like we're getting a standard-issue tough girl don't need no man (until they inevitably fall in love). Still hoping to be surprised, presumably Luc Besson knows what he's doing.

text: On one hand, I really liked Fifth Element, as well as Leon the Professional. On the other hand, I'm really not feeling the young leads - without any context given in the trailer, it feels more like those crappy wish fulfillment YA flicks (Divergent, Maze Runner, etc.) rather than a thoughtful sci-fi. Nevertheless, I really like the presence of Ethan Hawke, John Goodman, and hell, Dane DeHaan too (just wish his character was older in-story)!  Two other things:  * I don't know what the source material is like (and I'm not finding out now because I want the storyline of the film to surprise me), but some footage here makes me hopeful there's more of an "European" approach to relationships, so to speak. Countless Hollywood films (and others, taking after them), have a large chunk devoted to establishing romantic relationship between two leads in a very specific and perfunctory way, from first meeting to first sex scene, more-or-less, which ends up feeling really stilted and cookie-cutter, practically interchangeable from film to film. Hoping you'll take your chance to do things differently, and expose your viewers to a broader range of human experience!  * Sci-fi writers are often mocked for overly willing to use crazy numbers,  but here, you might've actually been too conservative in regards to the city of Alpha. You say there are thousands of species in it, and yet its population is 17 million, which is smaller than modern-day Shanghai, Beijing and Karachi (24, 21 and 23 million). Is this some extra-advanced population control at work, or are all other species like elephants, with long lives and slow reproduction cycles? )  Either way, wish you luck! We are really lacking in good soft sci-fi films, so I hope you can score a success here!

text: I can't believe no one's saying this but Valerian is going to be one of the most important sci-fi movies of our lives. Star Wars, Mass Effect, you name it they probably in some way ripped off or were inspired by Val√©rian and Laureline, the 1960's comic series, with Star Wars even stealing entire scenes and frames straight from the comic strips. Virtually no one gave the creators any credit for years even though they had basically created the entire sc-fi genre that we know today. Does it look like a generic space opera? Yes? But guess what? All those generic space operas took from Val√©rian and Laureline. It's only fair that they finally get some damn credit.

text: FOR THOSE WHO COMPLAIN ABOUT THE LACK OF PLOT RELATED INFORMATIONS IN THIS TEASER READ THIS: "Valerian et Laur√©line" is originally a french comics series telling the story of Valerian, a time-space traveler who meets during one of his mission on Earth a young peasant girl from the XI th century: Laureline. Laureline discovers that Valerian is a time-traveler, and so he is forced to take her with him back to the future. Laureline being an independant and impulsive smart-ass girl with a good brain she turns out to be the perfect companion for the always so-cool dependable and diligent Valerian who works for "Galaxity", capital of the Terran Galactic Empire. They stick together and we follow their adventures through space and time, adventures filled with monsters, political plots, discoveries, and unforgettable encounters (...and way too much sexual tension).  And it's great! This is the plot of the comics series, so maybe ( I hope!) it will be the same for the movie!  I hope I could help. :)

text: I'm very excited for this movie, as based upon the comics I used to read. I used to always love reading Heavy Metal magazine for the stories as well. Great stuff.  Plus Paul and Ringo allowed the used of one of the Beatle songs! WOW! Luc Besson really, never makes a bad film.  Lots of people first hated the 5th Element and I reminded people it's actually inspired by Valerian and a short story series from Heavy Metal which was what inspired the story of Harry, the Cab Driver in Heavy Metal,  the movie.  In 1978, this movie was groundbreaking and launched a platinum album the double gate Heavy Metal Album, Featuring songs by Nazareth, Black Sabbath, Sammy Hagar (Heavy Metal), Devo, and Don Felder's Heavy Metal which was a huge hit.  This movie, great expectations for this one.  I was a film major, and yea, I could tear apart many, many scripts but one day I realized, they're just movies and just enjoy them for what they are worth.  Some more than others....or less.. At the end of the day, I they are doing something I'm not yet doing, making great films even if the main audience doesn't get it. At least they are trying to bring us something despite the executives that finance these films and ruin them with their "opinions".  All in all, this should be a cool ass film.

text: For those who are unaware, which is probably almost everyone, this movie is based on a few-decades-old comic book series that INFLUENCED STAR WARS. Yes, you read that correctly. Certain plot points in Star Wars were INFLUENCED by the guy who created this originally. Which means this in many ways is the movie presentation of the grandfather of the most grand space opera ever to be created. There is no shortage of scifi lunacy to be enjoyed here. Just hope the director is good enough to live up to the task. If he pulls this off to it's fullest potential, it would put him on a level above George Lucas. This is on my watchlist. It has my interest so far. Something tells me in my gut that this is going to be much bigger than anyone expects.
